title: Want To Buy:  Wanted Colt AR15A4
postcontent: I am a disabled (in a wheelchair) former Hunter and former gunsmith.  I gave up the sport of hunting for meat mostly because I lived in California and the options disappeared as firearms laws became more draconian.I am on Social Security Disability, so far from wealthy by any shot.  So I can't slam down MSRP on a rifle.  I don't even have any savings to buy one.  So this will go on a credit card (if you have a way to take one, such as PayPal/Square/Whatever it would help).I think from a wheelchair, the AR-15 is a decent platform to sling over my back as I go and use both arms to propel myself through the woods, and the handle of a model such as the Colt AR15A4 can help safely hold the rifle if I need to hold and propel with the same hand.  Plus it is a decent platform for us southpaws as well.My intention is to mount a decent appropriate scope on the handle to retain it for its intended use, bit to have an accurate hunting rifles I can upgrade as needed.Now I am looking for a "like new" rifle, clean, in good repair, ready to "take out of the case, load, and hunt".  If it already has an optical sight or other features attached, that is a "bonus" so I don't have to do anything more with it.Food stamps for my roommate and I are less than $80 COMBINED, and I would like to fill my freezer for the cost of a "hunting license and a box of ammo" each year.I can come to you or if you are able to come up to the Mansfield area, that can work as well.I am just looking for the right price and to be able to negotiate something that is fair for all.I am willing to entertain other brands of AR-15 platform rifles as well as other calibers, but at a MINIMUM I want the quality of a "Colt"/"Sig"/"Smith&Wesson" not some "Hi-Point" type of brand...basically if they never had an article on them in American Rifleman with a decent review I am not interested.Now, I am not trying to be "smug" since "beggars can't be choosers"...but try to imagine this situation...I am in the woods alone except for my roommate (he is disabled as well, he has cerebral palsy but is able to walk unlike me) and we are hunting in crappy Ohio weather.  I want to insure we will be safe, that the firearm will fully be functional and accurate.  So my roommate and I come back safe and with meat.I was trained to hunt by a former USMC Sniper as a child (a friend of the family) a truly humble man...he taught me to "hunt like a sniper" basically "one shot, one kill" because there is NO REASON an animal should ever suffer.  So rarely did I need to fire a second shot to dispatch an animal after a "sloppy shot" (I have also been a "handgun Hunter" which from a wheelchair allows me to "park myself" let the animal come to me and requires more skill than a rifle...so my rifle hunting is more a "revolver Hunter" style than a "distance rifle Hunter").  I also am NOT a trophy Hunter...a "rack" or a "head" means nothing to me.  It is the meat and not waisting any of the animal (gone camping and hunted, "field dressed" the animal, cleaned it in camp and packed the meat on ice and put the "trimmings" and "sweetbreads" in the clean intestines and smoked sausage over the campfire...made blankets and clothing out of the pelts).  So I am far from anyone who is looking to have some "trophy on the wall".  I just want to eat more than once a day.I will be 50 on 22-July-2018, and I want a decent rifle I can hunt with for the rest of my life...offer some home security as well from a wheelchair...and pass it down on my death to someone who would appreciate it.  So I just want a "decent rifle" and not some "junk" rifle.Thank you very much,JohnPS: I left the price set at "0" since I don't know what is appropriate to put in and all things are negotiable as long as the offers are within my means and meet my terms as outlined above.

title: For Sale:  NEW 2018 I.D. MRE's!
postcontent: These are genuine mil-spec MRE's, not the cheap commercial wanna-be "camping meals". These are Case B, which has an assortment of 12 meals. With 12 meals per case, at this price, it is only $6.25 a meal for food that you can take anywhere with no refrigeration and still have a hot meal with loads of accessories such as crackers/bread, cheese/jelly spread, coffee, sugar, creamer, gum, Tabasco sauce, matches, and even toilet paper! These come with a water-activated heater for the entree, and detailed directions on how to use it (basically, just pour water into the bag and wait a few minutes). I also have spare heaters that I can provide so that you can heat up accessories as well. The dates on the boxes are the Inspection Date, not the expiration date.Here is a guide to the date codes on the cases:  The first line is the date it was manufactured. The number before the dash is a combination of the last digit of the year of manufacture and the Julian date of that year.  The number after the dash is the lot number of that date that the case belongs to.  So for the case in the picture, it was manufactured in 2015 on June 4th, and was part of the first lot produced that day.  The second line is the Inspect/Test date.  The number before the dash is the last two digits of the year, and the number after the dash is the month after which it is supposed to be tested/inspected before being consumed.  For the case in the picture, the inspect/test date is June of 2018 (three years after manufacture).  You can check this for yourself here: http://www.mreinfo.com/mres/mre-date-converter/As you can see in the pictures, these cases haven't even reached their first inspection date yet!THESE ARE LEGAL TO OWN, so please don't be an internet lawyer and try to enforce a law that doesn't exist.
